One of the main things that we like to do is always give options to the interns. So

00:13:56.159 --> 00:14:04.000
a number of interns are reporting to me now. And on their first week, I make sure that I have

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:10.320
always a list of projects, ideas that we believe are interesting, that we don't know how well they

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:16.799
will work eventually. But we know there's something to start with. We have some data

00:14:16.799 --> 00:14:23.919
somewhere, potentially, sometimes part of the project is collecting data from external sources

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:31.440
or producing it. And out of this list, then it's a bit of a skill and interest matching problem.

00:14:32.159 --> 00:14:37.119
So what we're doing really is saying like, what really don't you want to learn? What don't you

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:44.400
want to do while you're here in the four or eight or 12 months that you're here? And what do you want

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:52.080
to learn? What do you feel familiar with? And then they pick projects, I give them time over the week

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:57.760
to read about the projects, there's always supporting documentation, and our conversations

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:05.599
with me and other team members. And then they get to own that project over the length of their

00:15:05.599 --> 00:15:11.359
internship. And if they hit a milestone early, there's always flexibility. If they want to do

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:17.039
some work on what I would call like something that's already on the roadmap for like the next

00:15:17.039 --> 00:15:23.039
quarter, that's already like, owned by a different team, then they can split their time. But something

00:15:23.039 --> 00:15:29.359
that we do try to do is always have an intern own the project, be the main contributor,

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:35.840
make sure that they can then explain what that project and that the value of that product is to

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:42.799
other stakeholders. So we have them interact with product managers, with directors, and

00:15:43.679 --> 00:15:51.200
VPs often. So it's really part of building those communication skills, building that sense of

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:57.840
ownership, which make people care about the projects, make people care about what they're

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:04.320
learning a lot more if they're like the single source of progress for the for a project for a

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:10.479
while. And then we always try again to support them with other full time full time team members,

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:21.919
myself included, and doing a lot of meetings across essentially the internship. So yeah,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:27.760
so that's that's part of our program. It's, it's been successful so far. So a lot of these

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:32.799
projects, they're moving in two different phases. Some of them released some of them in

