do that is so amazing. So if you have the chance to be a mentor for somebody or a mentee, I highly

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:33.920
suggest everybody here. I have been a mentor myself as well. And there is a reverse mentoring

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:39.280
experience that happens when you mentor people for sure. So have you found that that's true? Like

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:44.880
you learn a lot from your people you mentor? Absolutely. And there's something also,

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:49.760
there's very valuable having people who are like, let's say you've been at the company for four

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:58.319
years. And then you say, hey, could you mentor that person? It also allows people who are just

00:17:58.319 --> 00:18:05.680
deep into the software, the problems and such to force them to teach it to someone else who has

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:11.680
like extremely little context, because again, they're an intern. They may be in their second

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:17.920
year of university. So the tools are new, the problems are new, everything is new, as opposed

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:22.880
to like onboarding someone who's like another senior developer. Again, they may know the tools,

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:28.959
they may have context already. So I think people start from scratch and go, okay, yeah, how do I

00:18:28.959 --> 00:18:34.160
teach this thing? What is missing from our documentation, from my mental model of how

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:39.599
things work? Am I hitting an edge case that's just kind of happened to work well, but now someone is

00:18:39.599 --> 00:18:44.800
questioning, like, why does it work that way? All of those are really good questions for people

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:52.160
who are just kind of, yeah, doing day to day work. And it forced them to reframe a few things. And I

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:58.800
think that's really good for avoiding those bits where there's internal knowledge, like tribal

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:04.640
knowledge that's just like in the heads of a few people, having them teach interns, even though

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:10.719
the interns will leave the organization after a few months. It makes people realize, oh, we've

00:19:10.719 --> 00:19:20.000
got those gaps. We have to improve a few things. And then, like you mentioned, it also just allows

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:26.719
us to learn a few more things because of those perspectives. Yeah. It sounds like that could be

00:19:26.719 --> 00:19:33.199
a really uncomfortable thing, having an intern or anybody, a mentee coming and poking holes in

00:19:33.199 --> 00:19:40.079
your reality and asking questions and stuff. But it's so valuable. And I think that that is a really,

00:19:40.079 --> 00:19:44.959
really valuable thing for anybody who's writing documentation. Get people who don't understand

